    <!-- MYTH BOX -->
    <div class="myth-box">
      <div class="myth-label">The Question Everyone Has</div>
      <h3>"Doesn't the Liver Store Toxins? Why Would I Eat It?"</h3>
      <p>This is the most common objection to eating liver, and it's based on a fundamental misunderstanding of what the liver actually does. <strong>The liver's job is to filter and neutralize toxins — and then excrete them from the body.</strong> It does not store the toxins it processes.</p>
      <p>What the liver does store is an exceptional concentration of vitamins and minerals. It's essentially a nutrient warehouse: B12, vitamin A, iron, copper, zinc, folate, and CoQ10 accumulate in the liver because they're needed throughout the body on demand. The liver is nutrient-dense <em>because</em> it's a metabolically active organ doing serious work — not despite it.</p>
      <p>The same logic applies to capsules made from liver. You're getting the concentrated micronutrients, not the toxins the liver processed and excreted during the animal's life. This is one myth worth retiring permanently.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What This Actually Means for Muscle Maintenance After 40</h2>

    <p>Here's the framing that matters for men focused on <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sarcopenia-men-over-40/">sarcopenia prevention</a> and holding onto muscle after 40: beef liver and organ supplements are micronutrient support tools, not muscle-building tools. The distinction matters.</p>

    <p>Several of liver's standout nutrients directly support the environment for muscle protein synthesis. Zinc is a cofactor in testosterone production and protein synthesis pathways. B12 is essential for the energy metabolism that fuels cellular repair. Heme iron supports oxygen delivery to muscle tissue — and iron deficiency is more common in active men over 40 than most people realize. CoQ10 (primarily from heart in organ blends) supports mitochondrial function, which underpins cellular energy at every level.</p>

    <p>None of these replace hitting your <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-per-day-after-40/">daily protein target</a>. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">Anabolic resistance</a> after 40 means your muscles are less sensitive to the protein signal — but the answer to that is more protein and better distribution, not micronutrients. Think of organ nutrition as the support crew: it keeps the machinery running well, but the fuel is still protein grams, tracked and hit consistently.</p>

    <!-- BOTTOM LINE BOX -->
    <div class="bottom-line">
      <h3>The Actual Decision Framework</h3>
      <p><strong>If you'll eat real liver:</strong> Once a week, 3 oz, cooked simply. This is the highest-value, lowest-cost option available. Soak it in milk first if the taste bothers you. Nothing in a capsule matches a full serving of the real thing.</p>
      <p><strong>If you won't eat it:</strong> Liver-only capsules (freeze-dried, grass-fed, transparent labeling) get you the liver micronutrient profile in a format you'll actually use consistently. Expect to take 6 capsules for roughly half a serving equivalent. It's not the same as eating liver, but it's real and it works.</p>
      <p><strong>If you want broader organ coverage:</strong> Multi-organ blends are legitimate, but read the label. If individual organ amounts aren't disclosed, the proprietary blend is doing the marketing, not the nutrition. The CoQ10 argument for heart inclusion is real — if you want CoQ10 specifically, it's a valid reason to choose a blend over liver-only.</p>
      <p><strong>What none of these do:</strong> Show up in your protein total. A full serving of organ capsules is 2–3g of protein. Everything else you're doing — the tracking, the daily target, the distribution across meals — still has to happen. The protein number still needs to be hit.</p>
    </div>

