    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between beef liver supplements and beef organ supplements?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Beef liver supplements contain only freeze-dried liver — one organ, concentrated. Beef organ supplements are multi-organ blends, typically combining liver, heart, kidney, and spleen. The blend gives you broader nutrient coverage: heart adds CoQ10, kidney adds selenium. The tradeoff is dilution — you get less of liver's standout nutrients (B12, vitamin A, copper) per capsule compared to a liver-only product at the same dose.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is eating real beef liver better than taking liver capsules?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">For nutrient density and protein, yes. A 3-ounce serving of real liver delivers 23g of complete protein plus the full nutrient profile in its most bioavailable form. Six liver capsules are equivalent to roughly 1/2 to 1 oz of fresh liver — a fraction of a full serving. Capsules are a practical option for people who won't eat real liver, but the real food version is superior on every nutritional metric.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do beef organ supplements count toward my daily protein intake?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">No — not meaningfully. A standard serving of organ supplements (6 capsules, ~3,000mg) contains approximately 2–3 grams of protein. These are micronutrient supplements, not protein sources. They support the cellular and hormonal environment for muscle maintenance — but they don't replace hitting your daily protein target.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is beef liver good for muscle building after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Beef liver supports the environment for muscle maintenance through several key micronutrients — zinc for testosterone and protein synthesis, heme iron for oxygen delivery to muscle, B12 for energy metabolism, CoQ10 for cellular energy. It doesn't build muscle directly, but the deficiencies it addresses can limit how effectively your protein and training convert into maintained muscle mass.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does beef liver store toxins?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">No. The liver filters and neutralizes toxins, then excretes them — it does not store them. What the liver stores is an exceptional concentration of vitamins and minerals. You are eating a nutrient warehouse, not a toxin warehouse. This is one of the most persistent misconceptions about organ meat and it isn't supported by how the liver actually functions.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How often should men over 40 eat beef liver?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Once or twice per week is the standard recommendation. A single 3-ounce serving delivers several days' worth of vitamin A and copper — both fat-soluble nutrients that accumulate at high doses. One to two servings per week captures the full micronutrient benefit without risk of excess. If you're using capsules at standard doses (3,000–6,000mg/day), you're well within safe limits.</div>
      </div>

